data.description: With quick beating or palpitation; pitapat. Congreve.
One of a sect of ancient Christians, who, in supposed imitationof the first believers, renounced all their possessions.
A genus of plants, one species of which (A. Mexicanum) haslavender-blue flowers in dense clusters.
Same as Angiospermous.
Belonging to the Aplacentata; without placenta.
Producing reeds or canes.
The act of ascertaining; a reducing to certainty; a finding outby investigation; discovery.The positive ascertainment of its limits. Burke.
An earnest; earnest money; money paid to bind a bargain.[Scot.] Arles penny, earnest money given to servants. Kersey.
A transparent or translucent variety of common feldspar, ororthoclase, which often shows pearly opalescent reflections; --called by lapidaries moonstone.
Liable to be lost. [R.]
Efficacious against syphilis.-- n.
Earlier form of Acknow. [Obs.] To be aknow, to acknowledge; toconfess. [Obs.]
Made friends; reconciled. [Obs.] "Deadly foes . . .affriended." Spenser.
Angulous. [R.]
One who annuls. [R.]
Rejection by judicial sentence. [R.] Knowles.
The condition or state of being free from fever.
Alacrity. [Obs.] Hammond.
In an acute manner; sharply; keenly; with nice discrimination.
Of or in the Christian church or era, anterior to the firstcouncil of Nice, held a. d. 325; as, antenicene faith.
A porridge or gruel of maize meal and water, milk, or the like.[Sp. Amer.]
A diseased condition produced by slow poisoning with arsenic.
Belonging to antipathy; opposite; contrary; allopathic.
Aromatic. [Obs.] Caxton.
A snatching away. [Obs.]
Warm contention in words; dispute carried on with heat oranger; controversy; wrangle; wordy contest. "Stormy altercations."Macaulay.
A name in the East Indies and the Indian islands for all ardentspirits. Arrack is often distilled from a fermented mixture of rice,molasses, and palm wine of the cocoanut tree or the date palm, etc.
To go or move upward upon or along; to climb; to mount; to goup the top of; as, to ascend a hill, a ladder, a tree, a river, athrone.
That part of the breast of an animal which extends from thefore legs back beneath the ribs; also applied to the fore part of ahorse, from the shoulders to the bottom of the chest.
The trunk or stem of a tree, or that which is like it.Enormous elm-tree boles did stoop and lean. Tennyson.
Prolonged at the base, as certain leaves.
To sprinkle with, or as with, stars; to decorate with, or aswith, stars; to bestud. "Bestarred with anemones." W. Black.

"A wooden pin stuck anciently on the sides of the bedstead, tohold the clothes from slipping on either side." Johnson.Hostess, accommodate us with a bedstaff. B. Jonson.Say there is no virtue in cudgels and bedstaves. Brome.
A variety of bacterium; a microscopic, rod-shaped vegetableorganism.

The part of a ship which is ordinarily under water; hence, thevessel itself; a ship.My ventures are not in one bottom trusted. Shak.Not to sell the teas, but to return them to London in the samebottoms in which they were shipped. Bancroft.Full bottom, a hull of such shape as permits carrying a large amountof merchandise.
Moving with a bound or bounds.The bounding pulse, the languid limb. Montgomery.

The chips or fragments made by boring. Boring bar, a revolvingor stationary bar, carrying one or more cutting tools for dressinground holes.-- Boring tool (Metal Working), a cutting tool placed in a cutterhead to dress round holes. Knight.
A short bar used by thieves to wrench doors open. [Written alsobettee.]The powerful betty, or the artful picklock. Arbuthnot.
To jumble together.
In a clumsy manner.
Spreading widely.
An African genet (Genetta pardina). See Genet.
To convert into, or make, good.To bonify evils, or tincture them with good. Cudworth.
Bipolar quality.
A stock or handle for holding and rotating a bit; a brace.
Same as Germicide.

Any instrument showing the changes in the weight of theatmosphere; also, less appropriately, any instrument that indicates -or foreshadows changes of the weather, as a deep vial of liquidholding in suspension some substance which rises and falls withatmospheric changes.
Resembling a bristle in form; as, a bristle-shaped leaf.
A friar of the Dominican order; -- called also predicant andpreaching friar; in France, Jacobin. Also, sometimes, a Benedictine.

Pertaining to, or invented by, Brown; -- a term applied to asystem of medicine promulgated in the 18th century by John Brown, ofScotland, the fundamental doctrine of which was, that life is a stateof excitation produced by the normal action of external agents uponthe body, and that disease consists in excess or deficiency ofexcitation.
High as the breast.
See Bort.
To make fast, as a rope, by taking several turns with it rounda pin, cleat, or kevel. Totten.
A projecting mass of masonry, used for resisting the thrust ofan arch, or for ornament and symmetry.
One that bursts.
Having an active or vigorous mind. [Colloq.]
A thicket of canes. Ellicott.
In a running or hasty manner; carelessly.
One who caricatures.
The Angora goat. See Angora goat, under Angora.
A native of China; a Chinese.
An instrument for cutting into the fetal head, to facilitatedelivery.
Methyl alcohol, CH3OH; -- also, by extension, any one in thehomologous series of paraffine alcohols of which methyl alcohol isthe type.
A red nose. Shak.
Without a carpet.
A method of taking photographic pictures, on paper sensitizedwith iodide of silver; -- also called Talbotype, from the inventor,Mr. Fox. Talbot.
Made or contrived for getting small sums of money from theignorant or unwary; as, a catchpenny book; a catchpenny show.-- n.
Relating to, or having the properties of, a caustic curveformed by reflection. See Caustic, a. Nichol.
Of or pertaining to the thigh or leg, or to any of the partscalled crura; as, the crural arteries; crural arch; crural canal;crural ring.
The first word of any page of a book after the first, insertedat the right hand bottom corner of the preceding page for theassistance of the reader. It is seldom used in modern printing.
A blowing together, as of many instruments in a concert, or ofmany fires in a foundry. [R.] Bacon.
A joint cause. Fotherby.

Any device in which an imperfectly conducting contact betweenpieces of metal or other conductors loosely resting against eachother is materially improved in conductivity by the influence ofHertzian waves; -- so called by Sir O. J. Lodge in 1894 on theassumption that the impact of the electic waves caused the looselyconnected parts to cohere, or weld together, a condition easilydestroyed by tapping. A common form of coherer as used in wirelesstelegraphy consists of a tube containing filings (usually a pinch ofnickel and silver filings in equal parts) between terminal wires orplugs (called conductor plugs).
See Chrysoberyl.
The dried meat of the cocoanut, from which cocoanut oil isexpressed. [Written also cobra, copperah, coppra.]
One who is compos mentis. [Colloq.]
Of, pertaining to, or derived from, the celandine. Cheidonicacid, a weak acid extracted fron the celandine (Chelidonium majus),as a white crystalline substance.
Controversial. [Obs.] Bp. Hall.
An offering made to the church at the interment of a dead body.Blackstone.

A name applied to various marine univalve shells; esp. to thoseof the genus Strombus, which are of large size. S. gigas is the largepink West Indian conch. The large king, queen, and cameo conchs areof the genus Cassis. See Cameo.
The act of certifying.
The native name of certain South American monkeys of the genusAteles, esp. A. paniscus. The black-faced coaita is Ateles ater. SeeIllustration in Appendix.
Rendering a criminal process civil. [Obs.]
Having the nerves spring from the midrib.
Frequent; numerous. [Obs.] Goodwin.
To delineate. [Obs.]These two stones as they are here defigured. Weever.
Hard; inflexible; obstinate; sour in aspect; hardy; bold.[Scot.]A dour wife, a sour old carlin. C. Reade.
The state of being devoted, or set apart by a vow. [R.] Bp.Hurd.
An instrument or apparatus in which water is separated byevaporation or distillation; the part of a distilling apparatus inwhich the separation of the vapors is effected.
A piece of canvas fastened by lacing to the bonnet of a sail,to give it a greater depth, or more drop.
The office or dignity of a doge.
Soiled; sullied; of a dark or dusky color; dark brown; dirty."Scraps of dingy paper." Macaulay.
Disesteem; depreciation; disrepute. Bacon.
To free from being inclosed.
One who dissuades; a dehorter.
Absent-minded; lost in thought; abstracted.
Free from warmth of passion or feeling.
To pull off shoes or sandals from. [Obs.] Cockeram.
The act of disappropriating.
To deoxidize. [Obs.]
Resembling in structure a tree or shrub.
Act of taking up plants from beds.

Ownership of land; an estate or patrimony which one has in hisown right; absolute proprietorship; paramount or sovereign ownership.Public domain, the territory belonging to a State or to the generalgovernment; public lands. [U.S.]in the public domain may be used byanyone wihout restriction.-- Right of eminent domain, that superior dominion of the sovereignpower over all the property within the state, including thatpreviously granted by itself, which authorizes it to appropriate anypart thereof to a necessary public use, reasonable compensation beingmade.
Definitive; determinate; final. [Obs.] Sir H. Wotton.
Dominion; rule. [Obs.] Evelyn.

To free from infectious or contagious matter; to destroyputrefaction; to purify; to make innocuous.When the infectious matter and the infectious matter and theodoriferous matter are one . . . then to deodorize is to disinfect.Ure.
Unfriendly to society; contracted; selfish; as, dissocialfeelings.
A democrat. [R.] Burke.
A box from which dice are thrown in gaming. Thackeray.
Same as Dempster. [Scot.]
Declining; sloping.
Wild raving or debauchery. [R.] Prynne.
Same as Decastere.
Flowing apart or off; dissolving; not fixed. [R.] Bailey.
Esoteric doctrine or principles.
To a very great degree; beyond what is usual; surpassingly. Itsignifies more than very.
The epithelial lining of the ventricles of the brain and thecanal of the spinal cord; endyma; ependymis.
To deliver up by one government to another, as a fugitive fromjustice. See Extradition.
A sending out; emission. [Obs.] Sir T. Browne.
Erysipelatous.
A building up; construction. [Obs.] Cockeram.
Whatever pertains to the subject under consideration; allthings.More wise, more learned, more just, more everything. Pope.
Employed in, or designed for, exploration. "Exploring parties."Bancroft.
Same as Eisel. [Obs.] Shak.

An ethereal salt, or compound ether, consisting of an organicradical united with the residue of any oxygen acid, organic orinorganic; thus the natural fats are esters of glycerin and the fattyacids, oleic, etc.
Standing out of, or rising above, water. Gray.
To take by assault; to storm; to overcome; to vanquish; as, toexpugn cities; to expugn a person by arguments.
To drive out; to expel. [Obs.]If charity be thus excluded and expulsed. Milton.
An island in a river; an ait. [Obs.] "Osiers on their eights."Evelyn.
To become open, disclosed, or developed; to pass through aprocess of evolution. Prior.
One who extemporizes.

Uplifted; high; lofty; also, animated; noble; as, elevatedthoughts. Elevated railway, one in which the track is raisedconsiderably above the ground, especially a city railway above theline of street travel.
Full of ease; suitable for affording ease or rest; quiet;comfortable; restful. Shak.-- Ease"ful*ly, adv.-- Ease"ful*ness, n.
Having the anterior scutes extending around the tarsus on theinner side; -- said of certain birds.
Liable or deserving to be excommunicated; makingexcommunication possible or proper. "Persons excommunicable ." Bp.Hall.What offenses are excommunicable Kenle.
An overflow, or overflowing abundance. [R.] Ray.
A kind of exorcism by blowing with the breath. Jer. Taylor.
One who embosses.
To cast out; to evict; to dispossess; as, to eject tenants froman estate.
A ventral cartilaginous or bony element of the coracoid in theshoulder girdle of some vertebrates.
To exhaust or evaporate moisture from; to dry up. Sir T.Browne.
A small bundle or collection; a compact cluster; as, a fascicleof fibers; a fascicle of flowers or roots.
Woody. [Obs.] Skelton.
The fold of skin which covers the glans of the penis; theprepuce.
Hastily; immediately; instantly; on the spot; hotfloot. Gower.Custance have they taken anon, foothot. Chaucer.
A stranger. [Obs.] Spenser.
To be overbusy or unduly anxious about trifles; to make abustle or ado. Sir W. Scott.
Destitute of fire.
Furnished with leaves; leafy; as, a foliate stalk. Foliatecurve. (Geom.) Same as Folium.
A performer on the flute; a flautist. Busby.

Pertaining to fulminic and cyanuric acids, and designating anacid so called. Fulminuric acid (Chem.), a white, crystalline,explosive subatance, H3C3N3O3, forming well known salts, and obtainedfrom the fulnunates. It is isomeric with cyanuric acid, and hence isalso called isocyanuric acid.
The figure, statue, or bust, on the prow of a ship.
Copper sulphide, used to color glass. Hebert.
Of or pertaining to Finland, to the Finns, or to theirlanguage.-- n.
Flexible; pliant; pliable; easily bent; plastic; tractable.Wordsworth.
A small oleaceous tree (Chionanthus virginica), of the southernUnited States, having clusters of white flowers with slender petals.It is often cultivated.

A soft, heavy, brilliant glass, consisting essentially of asilicate of lead and potassium. It is used for tableware, and foroptical instruments, as prisms, its density giving a high degree ofdispersive power; -- so called, because formerly the silica wasobtained from pulverized flints. Called also crystal glass. Cf.Glass.

A signal consisting of a white flag with a black center, usedby the United States Weather Bureau to indicate that a local frost isexpected. It is used only in Florida and along the coasts of thePacific and the Gulf Mexico.
Fear; terror. [Obs.]
Having a flange or flanges; as, a flanged wheel.
A writer of fragments; as, the fragmentist of WolfenbÃ¼ttel.[R.]

An inclosed passage way for establishing and directing acurrent of air, gases, etc.; an air passage; esp.:(a) A compartment or division of a chimney for conveying flame andsmoke to the outer air.(b) A passage way for conducting a current of fresh, foul, or heatedair from one place to another.(c) (Steam Boiler) A pipe or passage for conveying flame and hotgases through surrounding water in a boiler; -- distinguished from atube which holds water and is surrounded by fire. Small flues arecalled fire tubes or simply tubes. Flue boiler. See under Boiler.-- Flue bridge, the separating low wall between the flues and thelaboratory of a reverberatory furnace.-- Flue plate (Steam Boiler), a plate to which the ends of the fluesare fastened; -- called also flue sheet, tube sheet, and tube plate.-- Flue surface (Steam Boiler), the aggregate surface of fluesexposed to flame or the hot gases.
State of flowers; flowers, collectively or in general.Tennyson.
A suction valve or check valve at the lower end of a pipe;esp., such a valve in a steam-engine condenser opening to the airpump.
A boat with a flat bottom and square ends; -- used for thetransportation of bulky freight, especially in shallow waters.
One who forbears. Tusser.
The freezing, or effect of a freezing, of some part of thebody, as the ears or nose. Kane.
A writer of fables; a fabulist; a dealer in untruths orfalsehoods. Br. Hall.
A suburb of French city; also, a district now within a city,but formerly without its walls.
Full of gladness; joyful; glad. [R.] -- Glad"ful*ness, n. [R.]Spenser.It followed him with gladful glee. Spenser.
To growl; to snarl.And wolves are gnarling who shall gnaw thee first. Shak.

An instrument for recording, preserving, and reproducingsounds, the record being a tracing of a phonautograph etched in somesolid material. Reproduction is accomplished by means of a systemattached to an elastic diaphragm.
To make glib. [Obs.] Bp. Hall.
Having a good temper; not easily vexed. See Good-natured.
Of or pertaining to the gyrostat or to gyrostatics.
The original native name for the ancient Ethiopic language orpeople. See Ethiopic.
A young hog.
Resembling granite in structure or shape.
A colorless liquid, obtained from certain derivatives ofglycerin, and regarded as a partially dehydrated glycerin; -- calledalso glycidic alcohol.
Dried grain, as oats or wheat, hulled and broken or crushed; inhigh milling, cracked fragments of wheat larger than grits. Embdengroats, crushed oats.
Of or pertaining to the chin; mental; as, the genianprominence.
In the manner of a gate.Three circles of stones set up gatewise. Fuller.
The production of offspring by the union of parents ofdifferent sexes; sexual reproduction; -- the opposite ofagamogenesis.
A lively French and Italian dance.
Of or pertaining to Galatia or its inhabitants.-- A native or inhabitant of Galatia, in Asia Minor; a descendant ofthe Gauls who settled in Asia Minor.
One who gushes. [Colloq.]
A small-sized, well-proportioned, Spanish horse; a jennet.Shak.
A series of beds of clay and marl in the South of England,between the upper and lower greensand of the Cretaceous period.
A summerhouse so situated as to command an extensive prospect.[Colloq.]
The quality of being governable; manageableness.
Any substance having a peculiar glassy appearance, and aconchoidal fracture, and usually produced by fusion.
Free from gestures.
A great boaster; a blusterer.
An unaccompanied part song for three or more solo voices. It isnot necessarily gleesome.
Becoming smooth or glabrous from age. Gray.
To render gentile or gentlemanly; as, to gentilize yourunworthy sones. [R.] Sylvester.
See Groan. [Obs.]
The art of employment of an historiographer.
Same as HÃ¦matoplastic.
To hie. [Obs.]Men must high them apace, and make haste. Holland.
Serving to discover or find out.
Sick at heart; extremely depressed in spirits; very despondent.
One skilled in the knowledge of plants; a collector of, ordealer in, herbs, especially medicinal herbs.
So as to heal or cure.
An hypogynous plant.
Of or relating to worms, or Helminthes; expelling worms.-- n.
One who is versed or skilled in hydrostatics. [R.]
A hydrous silicate of alumina and baryta, occurring usually inwhite cruciform crystals; cross-stone.
An apparatus for separating the threads of warps into sets, asthey are wound upon the reel from the bobbins, in a warping machine.
A harmless snake (Farancia abacura), found in the SouthernUnited States. The color is bluish black above, red below.
A herbalist. [Obs.]
Appearing as if one side, or one half, were cut away;dimidiate.
A blue isometric mineral, characteristic of some volcani
Destitute of hair. Shak.
Hateful; detestable. [Obs.]
Lame in the hip. [R.] Gower.
Developing, in the case of multicellular organisms, from thesame embryonic systems into which the secondary unit (gastrula orplant enbryo) differentiates.
A hygienist.
That part of the architrave which is over a door or window.
Emerging from the light of the sun, or passing into it; risingor setting at the same, or nearly the same, time as the sun. Sir T.Browne.
One versed in hygiene.
A ruffian; one who hounds, or spies upon, another; app. esp. tothe members of certain alleged societies among the Chinese. [U. S.]
Happening or done every hour; occurring hour by hour; frequent;often repeated; renewed hour by hour; continual.In hourly expectation of a martyrdom. Sharp.
Combined with hydrogen sulphide.
Same as Hydriodide.

An order of marsipobranchs including the lampreys. Thesuckerlike moth contains numerous teeth; the nasal opening is in themiddle of the head above, but it does not connect with the mouth. SeeCyclostoma, and Lamprey.
A nitrogenous substance, C8H7NO, isomeric with oxindol,obtained as an oily liquid.
A work of art or of human industry, of an early epoch;especially, a book printed before A. D. 1500.
Peerless; incomparable. [Obs.] Spenser.
The quality or state of being imperious; arrogance;haughtiness.Imperiousness and severity is but an ill way of treating men who havereason of their own to guide them. Locke.
One who believes in incorporealism. Cudworth.
In an inscrutable manner.
In an icy manner; coldly.Faultily faultless, icily regular, splendidly null, Dead perfection,no more. Tennyson.
One who, or that which, infuses.
To put in action. [Obs.]
Within or beneath a membrane; as, intermembranous ossification.
Intermundane. [Obs.]

A series of antiphons and responses, expressing the sorrowfulremonstrance of our Lord with his people; -- sung on the morning ofthe Good Friday in place of the usual daily Mass of the Roman ritual.Grove.
A kind of tape or braid. Shak.
In an intellective manner. [R.] "Not intellectivelly to write."Warner.
To insert as in a sheath; to sheathe. Hughes.
Being, between worlds or orbs. [R.] "Intermundane spaces."Locke.
To cultivate by planting simultaneous crops in alternate rows;as, to intercrop an orchard. Also, to use for catch crops at seasonswhen the ground is not covered by crops of the regular rotation.
Unequal; uneven; various. [Obs.] Chaucer.

Incapable of being conquered, overcome, or subdued;unconquerable; insuperable; as, an invincible army, or obstacle.Lead forth to battle these my sons Invincible. Milton.-- In*vin"ci*ble*ness, n.-- In*vin"ci*bly, adv.
In transit; during passage; as, goods in transitu.
In an inconvenient manner; incommodiously; unsuitably;unseasonably.
The larva of any geometrid moth. See Geometrid.
Pertaining to, or proceeding by, induction; inductive.
An inequality.
So as not to be effaceable.
In an insular manner.
A nitrogenous compound, C7H6N2, analogous to indol, andproduced from a diazo derivative or cinnamic acid.
That which is within; the interior. [Poetic] Mrs. Browning.
An oath.
A convulsive tic similar to or identical with miryachit,observed among the woodsmen of Maine.
After the manner of the Japanese; resembling japanned articles.Carlyle.
Made of jet, or like jet in color.The people . . . are of a jetty. Sir T. Browne.
Of or pertaining to Judea.-- n.
To run or strike against each other; to encounter; to clash; tojostle. Shak.The chariots shall rage in the streets; they shall justle one againstanother in the broad ways. Nahum ii. 4.
A cleft or division. Jag bolt, a bolt with a nicked or barbedshank which resists retraction, as when leaded into stone.
One who journeys.
Fringed with long, pendent hair.
To wet; to bemire. [Prov. Eng.] Halliwell.
A soldier armed with a javelin. Holland.
An extractive matter contained in the juice of the green shucksof the walnut (Juglans regia). It is used medicinally as analterative, and also as a black hair dye.
The planet Jupiter. [R.] Pope.
Jollity; merriment. [Obs.] Spenser.
A jacket or short coat; a close waistcoat. Shak.
One who judges. Sir K. Digby.
Uttering songs of triumph; shouting with joy; triumphant;exulting. "The jubilant age." Coleridge.While the bright pomp ascended jubilant. Milton.
Any small jumping rodent of the genus Dipus, esp. D. Ãgyptius,which is common in Egypt and the adjacent countries. The jerboas havevery long hind legs and a long tail. [Written also gerboa.]
A name given to a free-booting, unenlisted, armed man orguerrilla.
See Yawn. [Obs.] Marston.

The chief city of Palestine, intimately associated with theglory of the Jewish nation, and the life and death of Jesus Christ.Jerusalem artichoke Etym: [Perh. a corrupt. of It. girasole i.e.,sunflower, or turnsole. See Gyre, Solar.] (Bot.) (a) An Americanplant, a perennial species of sunflower (Helianthus tuberosus), whosetubers are sometimes used as food. (b) One of the tubers themselves.-- Jerusalem cherry (Bot.), the popular name of either of either oftwo species of Solanum (S. Pseudo-capsicum and S. capsicastrum),cultivated as ornamental house plants. They bear bright red berriesof about the size of cherries.-- Jerusalem oak (Bot.), an aromatic goosefoot (Chenopodium Botrys),common about houses and along roadsides.-- Jerusalem sage (Bot.), a perennial herb of the Mint family(Phlomis tuberosa).-- Jerusalem thorn (Bot.), a spiny, leguminous tree (Parkinsoniaaculeata), widely dispersed in warm countries, and used for hedges.-- The New Jerusalem, Heaven; the Celestial City.
A gem of an azure color. [Obs.]
Crowding; hustling.

To run against and shake; to push out of the way; to elbow; tohustle; to disturb by crowding; to crowd against. "Bullies jostledhim." Macaulay.Systems of movement, physical, intellectual, and moral, which areperpetually jostling each other. I. Taylor.
A boasting; a bragging. [Obs.]
The state or quality of being jocund; gayety; sportiveness.
Same as Juise. [Obs.] Chaucer.
To jest; to play tricks; to jeer. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A kind of whip for flogging criminals, formerly much used inRussia. The last is a tapering bundle of leather thongs twisted withwire and hardened, so that it mangles the flesh.
See Creatin.
To dry in a kiln; as, to kiln-dry meal or grain. Mortimer.
See Cacoxene.
An alcoholic liquor, obtained by distilling the fermented juiceof the small black cherry.
A unit of electromotive force equal to one thousand volts.
To form a key seat, as by cutting. See Key seat, under Key.
A species of gray fox found in Russia.
One of a negro tribe of Liberia and the adjacent coast, whosemembers are much employed on shipboard.
The hollow stalk of an umbelliferous plant, such as the cowparsnip or the hemlock. [Written also kex, and in pl., kecks, kaxes.]Nothing teems But hateful docks, rough thistles, kecksies, burs.Shak.
A kerchief. [Obs.]He became . . . white as a kercher. Sir T. North.
A house; esp., one which is a resort for thieves. [Slang, Eng.]
See Knowl, edge.We consider and knowleche that we have offended. Chaucer.
A vat or tub in which the mash is made; a mash tub. Ure.
A samara.
A small Russian coin. One hundred kopecks make a rouble, worthabout sixty cents. [Written also kopek, copec, and copeck.]

An officer in the household of the British sovereign, who hascognizance of transgressions within the royal household and verge,and of contracts made there, a member of the household being one ofthe parties. Wharton.
Leather prepared from the skin of young or small cattle,intermediate in grade between calfskin and cowhide.
To bruise; to grind coarsely; as, kibbled oats. [Prov.Eng.]Halliwell.
See Conite.
Having the legs bent inward so that the knees touch in walking.[Written also knack-kneed.]
Rough dressing by knocking off knobs or projections.
A mash vat. See Keeve. [Obs.]
Same as Calcimine.
Same as Cossack.
See Kinesiatrics.

Of or pertaining to a knight; becoming a knight; chivalrous;as, a knightly combat; a knightly spirit.For knightly jousts and fierce encounters fit. Spenser.[Excuses] full knightly without scorn. Tennyson.
To heave or to retch, as in an effort to vomit. [R.] Swift.

The only existing genus of Merostomata. It includes only a fewspecies from the East Indies, and one (Limulus polyphemus) from theAtlantic coast of North America. Called also Molucca crab, king crab,horseshoe crab, and horsefoot.
One of the Longirostres.
Crystallized litharge, obtained by fusion in the form of fineyellow scales.
One of the followers of Lucifer, bishop of Cagliari, in thefourth century, who separated from the orthodox churches because theywould not go as far as he did in opposing the Arians.
Muddy; slimy; thick. Sir T. Browne.
Lubric.
A bitter, white, crystalline substance found in orange andlemon seeds.
Like wood.

Having length; rather long or too long; prolix; not brief; --said chiefly of discourses, writings, and the like. "Lengthyperiods." Washington. "Some lengthy additions." Byron. "These wouldbe details too lengthy." Jefferson. "To cut short lengthyexplanations." Trench.
Same as Ligan. Brande & C.
Linear. Holland.
A larva.
One of a series of anhydrides of an amido type, analogous tothe lactones, as oxindol.
Any one of several species of small arctic rodents of thegenera Myodes and Cuniculus, resembling the meadow mice in form. Theyare found in both hemispheres.

The connection between sovereign and subject by which they weremutually bound, the former to protection and the securing of justice,the latter to faithful service; allegiance. [Written also ligeancyand liegance.] Chaucer.
Lobiped.
A vessel used to receive the washings of ores of metals.
To tear; to rend; to separate by tearing; to mangle; as, tolacerate the flesh. Hence: To afflict; to torture; as, to laceratethe heart.
